VGenerally speaking, the emulator is much slower than a device at CPU and GPU tasks
p13463
aVThat's for at least two reasons:
p13464
aVThe emulator is running ARM opcodes, converting them into equivalent x86 instructions, which is slow
p13465
aVDevices (usually) have graphics accelerators, whereas the emulated environment does not, despite whatever video card you have on the machine running the emulator
p13466
aVTo put things in perspective, I do my Android work on an Intel quad-core 2
p13467
aV66GHz with a fairly nice graphics card
p13468
aVFor videos that work fine on devices, I can sometimes get them to play back in the emulator
p13469
aVThe emulator is faster than a device, though, at "disk" I/O
p13470
aVWhen you write to "flash" on the emulator, you are writing to a disk image file that probably resides on a regular hard drive, assuming you're not using an SSD
p13471
aVActually writing to flash on a device can be massively slower -- Brad Fitzpatrick, at last week's Google I|O 2010 conference, cited spikes of up to 200ms to write a single byte to flash
p13472
aVAnd, the combination of Android, flash, and the yaffs2 filesystem apparently causes a device to get progressively slower at flash I/O as the flash fills up
p13473
aVHence, his recommendation was to do any flash writes in a background thread instead of the main application thread, where it can tie up the UI and lead to a "janky" app
p13474
aV(apparently, "janky" is a technical term
p13475
aV:-)
p13476
aVBTW, when it shows up online, definitely watch Brad's presentation on YouTube
p13477
aVIt may be a bit difficult to follow at times, because he spoke very quickly, but it was full of useful tidbits related to performance
